's attendance at school and health appointments. Looking beyond these statistics reveals a host of hidden costs for the mothers who meet the conditions. With a poignant voice and keen focus on ethnographic research, Tara Patricia Cookson turns the reader's gaze to women's care work in landscapes of grossly inadequate state investment, cleverly drawing out the tensions between social inclusion and conditionality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aColonies and colonization. Emigration and immigration. International migration. 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticxSocial aspectszPeru. 0aHistory (General). 0aRural womenzPeruxEconomic conditions. 0aWomen. Feminism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  abehavioral economists.  acct programs.  achanging behavior.  achildrens attendance.  aconditional cash transfer.  aefficiency.  aethnographic research.  afacing ordeals.  agood intentions.  agrossly inadequate state investment.  ahealth appointments.  ahidden costs.  alives and labors.  amainstream poverty alleviation programs.  amothers.  aperu.  apoor mothers.  arural poor.  aschool appointments.  asocial inclusion.  awomens care work.  aworld bank.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520969520zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969520zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520969520.jpg  a978-3-11-066767-7 UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA